      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Empirical evidence is mixed, but most mainstream economic studies do not support the idea that overall immigration significantly depresses native wages across the board. While some highly localized or low-skilled sectors might see minor wage pressure, the broader consensus is that immigrants tend to take jobs that native-born workers are less willing to do. Therefore, the claim that immigration universally hurts wages is often an oversimplification used in political rhetoric rather than a robust statistical finding.",
